        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov 20. 1879</date>
                    <salute>My dear Dyer,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>Can <hi rend="underline">you tell me the name of the enclosed Epimedium</hi>, &amp; I enclose an addressed post card to save you trouble. The long flower peduncles with yellow flowers come up separately from the leaves early in the spring out of doors.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                    <p>In the summer I asked for some Gossypium seeds, but you had none; if you have any now I should be grateful for a few; but only species producing large cotyledons, such as the Nankin cotton which I had formerly from Kew, would be of any use to me<ref target="#foot.f2"/>  Thompson of Ipswich sent me <hi rend="underline">G. herbaceum</hi> but these were of no use, and he has no other kind.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>My dear Dyer | Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The specimen was probably <hi rend="italic">Epimedium pinnatum</hi>, a perennial with bright yellow flowers in the family Berberidaceae. In <hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi>, p. 103, CD mentioned that the greatly elongated flower stems and petioles of the plant rose up independently of the leaves and broke through the ground in the shape of arches.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had requested <hi rend="italic">Gossypium maritimum</hi> and <hi rend="italic">G. brasiliense</hi> (both synonyms of <hi rend="italic">G. barbadense</hi>, Creole cotton) in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11950.xml">letter to Thiselton-Dyer of 24 March 1879</ref>. CD’s notes on the sleep of cotyledons in ‘Nankin cotton’, dated June, July, and August 1879, are in DAR 209.14: 5 and 15. Nankin is an alternative spelling for Nankeen; Nankeen cotton is <hi rend="italic">Gossypium nanking</hi> (a synonym of <hi rend="italic">G. arboreum</hi>, tree cotton). See <hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi>, pp. 22–3, 324.</note> 
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD’s notes on <hi rend="italic">Gossypium herbaceum</hi> (Levant cotton) received from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4728.xml">William Thompson</ref> are in DAR 209.5: 99–107; CD discussed the different behaviour of the cotyledons in Nankin cotton and <hi rend="italic">G. herbaceum</hi> in <hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi>, p. 303.</note> 
        </div>
    
